--- !u!114 &499242886
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 499242885}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: fc21bcdde9f33a640840daad2b7f5e8f, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::UserGuideManager
  entries:
  - title: Workspace / Canvas
    description: A certain area of the screen that acts as a canvas for hardware
      components, its purpose is to work on the placed components to interact to
      their contents it provides
    images:
    - {fileID: -1548875187287816032, guid: caf1fda0cd2222e4989f14f29fb2856d, type: 3}
  - title: Hardware Area
    description: A storage room for components that is not currently active in the
      workspace, dragging components inside hardware area and dropping to the workspace
      will activate the hardware so that player can interact with it.
    images:
    - {fileID: -2063781512671078472, guid: 6d1f3d4bd3ae2fa4cbe73f4917459106, type: 3}
  - title: Terminal / User Log
    description: 'A text display that shows the current log of the players recent
      interactions to the hardware, its purpose is to give feedback to the player
      if the actions is either: completed or not possible; requires other actions
      first.'
    images:
    - {fileID: -1240907655283256226, guid: c1c6d302509f2de408c4753be149d9fb, type: 3}
  - title: 'Task List '
    description: 'A progression task that guides the player on what steps they should
      follow that is inline to the required processses on a specified topic. It helps
      the player to see what process they should currently do


      The task list
      displays in two different ways. A general task list panel and a current single
      task displays that also follows the current players task. The general task
      list can be seen if a component''s detail view is not yet activated. otherwise
      it will display the single task display, that way it would not eat up the screen
      as well as player can still see the task without having to exit the detail
      view. (Refer to guide No. 6)'
    images:
    - {fileID: -1751934493417674604, guid: 01b618ea3a3d08a43b06b781a686039d, type: 3}
  - title: Drag & Drop
    description: When holding a left click on a component, it will invoke a drag
      function wherein you can manipulate its position on your commnad, releasing
      the hold will drop the currently dragged component
    images: []
  - title: Detail View
    description: Invoking right-click input on some component will activate their
      "Detail View", while inside the detail view; the player can now interact to
      certain content it provides depending on the components.
    images: []
  - title: Power Switches
    description: 'Some Hardware components posseses power switches. It has two states:
      power on and power off. In some most cases, before interacting to its component;
      it will require its power source to be first turned off.


      To power on
      and off the power switches, requires the player to some cases either: double
      mouse left-click or single mouse left-click input. A visual input will display
      the state of the power if it is at powered on or powered off state. '
    images: []
  - title: Cables
    description: "A connectors on which users must connect or disconnect the cables.
      In some cases, its component requires the cable to be first remove in order
      to invoke the \"Drag & Drop\" functions (Refer to guide No. 5). \n\nTo remove
      the cable, it requires the player to input a left-click mouse input and hold
      it until the cable is uninstalled, while holding, you have now the capicity
      to either drop it from the hardware are to completely uninstall, otherwise
      it will snap back to its port."
    images: []
  - title: Screws
    description: "A lock-mechanism, its purpose is to pin down the said components
      that is needed to be screwed. \n\nTo unscrew, drag the \"Screwdriver\" from
      the hardware are container from the left. Then aim the said component to the
      screw to unscrew. Screwing the screw will require a screw first, so drag the
      screw from the hardware area and drop it from the screwhole to first place
      an unscrewed screw to the screwhole, then drag the screwdriver again to screw
      the screw from the screwhole to screw the screw. "
    images: []
  - title: Latch/Lock
    description: 'In similiar of screws, the latch is also another lock-mechanism
      that does not require a screw but rather a snap installation method. In some
      cases, hardware will require their components to be latched on to their slot
      in order to lock its postition. Latching on a components requires a swipe-down
      gesture input, latching off requires swipe up. '
    images: []
  toggleButton: {fileID: 301020518}
  closeButton: {fileID: 1067989090}
  guidePanel: {fileID: 1752239172}
  navButtonContainer: {fileID: 1897950025}
  navNormalColor: {r: 0.8679245, g: 0.8679245, b: 0.8679245, a: 1}
  navSelectedColor: {r: 0.25, g: 0.55, b: 1, a: 1}
  searchField: {fileID: 1151021775}
  imageDisplay: {fileID: 1408196213}
  prevImageButton: {fileID: 770586590}
  nextImageButton: {fileID: 463268193}
  imagePageLabel: {fileID: 1342778224}
  noImageLabel: {fileID: 502680581}
  entryTitleText: {fileID: 2099612770}
  descriptionText: {fileID: 304693575}
